@page "/"

<PageTitle>Web Awesome Blazor Bindings</PageTitle>

<h1>Web Awesome Blazor Bindings</h1>

<p>
    Strongly-typed Blazor wrappers for the <a href="https://webawesome.com">Web Awesome</a> web components —
    idiomatic C# parameters and enums, EditForm and validation integration, named slots as render fragments,
    and a minimal JS interop surface. MIT-licensed; versions follow Web Awesome releases one-to-one.
</p>

<ExampleSection Title="Hello Web Awesome" Code="@HelloExample">
    <WaButton Variant="WaVariant.Brand" OnClick="() => count++">Click me</WaButton>
    <p>Clicked @count times</p>
</ExampleSection>

<h2>Getting started</h2>

<h3>1. Install</h3>
<pre><code>dotnet add package WebAwesome.Blazor</code></pre>

<h3>2. Register services</h3>
<pre><code>using WebAwesome.Blazor.Extensions;

builder.Services.AddWebAwesome(builder.Configuration);</code></pre>

<h3>3. Include assets</h3>
<p>Place the <code>WebAwesomeAssets</code> component in your head content (e.g. in <code>App.razor</code>):</p>
<pre><code>&lt;WebAwesomeAssets /&gt;</code></pre>
<p>
    In standalone WebAssembly apps (like this demo), add the equivalent static tags to <code>index.html</code> instead.
    See the <a href="https://github.com/boldbrick/WebAwesome-Blazor">repository README</a> for details.
</p>

<h3>4. Use components</h3>
<p>Pick any component from the sidebar to see live examples and its API reference.</p>

@code {
    private int count;

    private const string HelloExample = """
        <WaButton Variant="WaVariant.Brand" OnClick="() => count++">Click me</WaButton>
        <p>Clicked @count times</p>
        """;
}
